## Fix: SHACL per-class data properties and RDFS post-processing

### Context
After importing `shapes.ttl`, the UI showed 0 relationships and fewer than 46 entities because:
1. SHACL `sh:property` URIs are per-class (e.g. `ACTIF_GENERIQUEShape/acronyme`). Storing them as global DatatypeProperties with deduplication by name meant each property was attached to only the first class that declared it — all other classes lost their attributes.
2. `apply_parsed_rdfs_to_domain` did not call `sync_class_data_properties`, so global DatatypeProperties were never merged into class `dataProperties` lists.
3. "208 relationships" in the success message was misleading — they are data properties, not ObjectProperties.

### Changes

1. **`src/back/core/w3c/rdfs/RDFSParser.py`**
   - SHACL extraction in `get_classes()`: now builds `dataProperties` list directly on each class from its `sh:property` URI segments, so every class gets its own complete attribute list.
   - Removed SHACL property extraction from `get_properties()` — no global properties are emitted for pure SHACL files.

2. **`src/back/objects/ontology/Ontology.py`**
   - `apply_parsed_rdfs_to_domain()` — now calls `sync_class_data_properties()` after updating the domain, ensuring any global DatatypeProperties with domain references are also merged into class `dataProperties`.

### Modified Files
- `src/back/core/w3c/rdfs/RDFSParser.py`
- `src/back/objects/ontology/Ontology.py`

### Test Results
- 428 passed, 11 skipped — full suite green.
- `shapes.ttl`: 46 classes each with correct per-class `dataProperties` (e.g. `ACTIF_GENERIQUE` gets all 35 of its own attributes), 0 global properties.

